{"cursor":"3038","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox University President\n| name =Jeremiah Chaplin image =Jeremiah chaplin colby.jpeg caption = order =\n| university =Founder and President of Colby College term_start =1822 term_end\n| =1833 order2 = university2 = birth_date = birth_place =Rowley, Massachusetts\n| (now Georgetown, Massachusetts death_date = death_place =Hamilton, New York\n| predecessor = successor =Rev. Rufus Babcock alumnus =Brown University\n| residence = profession = religion =Baptist spouse = children = website =\n| footnotes = }}\n'Jeremiah Chaplin' (January 2, 1776 â€“ May 7, 1841) was a Reformed Baptist\ntheologian who served as the first president of Colby College (then called the\nWaterville College) in Maine.\n\nChaplin was born in Rowley, Massachusetts (now Georgetown, Massachusetts) in\n1776. He worked on the family farm, and in 1799 he graduated from Brown\nUniversity, a school with an historical Baptist affiliation. Chaplin spent a\nyear at Brown as a tutor and then studied theology eventually becoming pastor of\na Baptist church in Danvers, Massachusetts. He left this pastorate in 1817 to\nbecome president of the new Waterville College (later Colby College) at which he\nserved until 1833. Chaplin first met Gardner Colby during this period while\nColby was still a child, and Chaplin assisted Colby's family after Colby's\nfather died.\n\nDuring the remainder of his life, Chaplin preached in Rowley, Massachusetts and\nWilmington, Connecticut, and then moved to Hamilton, New York where he died in\n1841. Chaplin held to a Calvinist Baptist theology throughout his life. [ht-\ntp://books.google.com/books?id=a1FAAAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=f-\nalse Eulogy of Jeremiah Chaplin (1843)]\n","linknr":107,"url":"Jeremiah_Chaplin","recorded":1375060855,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Jeremiah_Chaplin&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Jeremiah_Chaplin&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/op